d of 16)<br>2nd (DNQ)\n|''Did not qualify''\n|-\n|[[2017-18 Tiburones Rojos de Veracruz season|2017\u201318]]\n|[[2017\u201318 Liga MX season|1]]\n|17th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|16th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|2nd (DNQ)<br>3rd (DNQ)\n|''Did not qualify''\n|-\n|[[2018-19 Tiburones Rojos de Veracruz season|2018\u201319]]\n|[[2018\u201319 Liga MX season|1]]\n|18th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|18th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|3rd (DNQ)<br>1st (Quarter-finals)\n|''Did not qualify''\n|-\n|[[2019-20 Tiburones Rojos de Veracruz season|2019\u201320]]\n|[[2019\u201320 Liga MX season|1]]\n|19th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|Disaffiliated\n|''Did not qualify''\n|2nd (DNQ)\n|''Did not qualify''\n|}\n\n==Club Records==\n* '''Longest undefeated streak:''' 18 (1945\u201346)\n* '''Most game without a draw:''' 19 (Invierno '99)\n* '''Most games without a win:''' 40 (Clausura 2019)\n* '''Longest winning streak:''' 8 (1945\u201346 y Apertura 2004)\n* '''longest draw streak:''' 5 (1990\u201391)\n* '''Longest losing streak:''' 9 (Verano 2002)\n* '''Longest scoring streak:''' 28 (1946\u201347)\n* '''Longest streak without a goal:''' 4 (1970\u201371)\n* '''Longest streak with allowing a goal:''' 4 (1967\u201368 e Invierno 2000)\n* '''Biggest win:''' 14\u20130 May 26, 1946 vs. [[C.F. Monterrey|Monterrey]]\n* '''Biggest loss:''' 9\u20132 April 13, 2019 vs. [[C.F. Pachuca]] Veracruz vs. 0-7 Necaxa\n\n\n===All time top Goalscorers===\n\nThese are the top 10 all time goal scorers in the club history.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090803234542/http://www.tiburones-rojos.com/historia/records/ Clubs Records]</ref>\n\n{| cellpadding=\"3\" cellspacing=\"0\" border=\"1\" style=\"background:#f7f8ff; margin:auto; font-size:95%; border:gray solid 1px; border-collapse:collapse;\"\n|- style=\"background:#ddd; text-align:center; color:black;\"\n!width=\"40\"|Position\n! style=\"width:220px;\"|Player\n! style=\"width:160px;\"|Goals\n! style=\"width:140px;\"|Years\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|1\n|[[File:Flag of Brazil.svg|20px|Brazil]] Mariano Ubiracy\n|98\n|1965\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|2\n|[[File:Flag of Mexico.svg|20px|Argentina]] [[Luis de la Fuente (Mexican footballer)|Luis \"Pirata\" de la Fuente]]\n|83\n|1943\u201352\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|3\n|[[File:Flag of Mexico.svg|20px|Chile]] Raymundo \"Pel\u00f3n\" Gonz\u00e1lez\n|77\n|1986\u201396\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|4\n|[[File:Flag of Argentina.svg|20px|Uruguay]] [[Jorge Comas (footballer)|Jorge Comas]]\n|77\n|1989\u201394\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|5\n|[[File:Flag of Chile.svg|20px|Chile]] Jos\u00e9 Luis \"Loco\" Auss\u00edn\n|65\n|1964-1971\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|6\n|[[File:Flag of Argentina.svg|20px|Mexico]] Jorge Enrico\n|54\n|1943\u201349\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|7\n|[[File:Flag of Uruguay.svg|20px|Brazil]] Ricardo Brand\u00f3n\n|45\n|1976\u201378\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|8\n|[[File:Flag of Uruguay.svg|20px|Mexico]] [[Gustavo Biscayzac\u00fa|Gustavo \"El Grillo\" Biscayzac\u00fa]]\n|43\n|2004\u201306\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|9\n|[[File:Flag of Mexico.svg|20px|Spain]] Jes\u00fas \"Chucho\" Hern\u00e1ndez\n|39\n|????\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|10\n|[[File:Flag of Mexico.svg|20px|Mexico]] Pedro Dami\u00e1n\n|36\n|????\n|}\n\n===Goal scoring champions===\n:* '''[[Copa M\u00e9xico]] 1943\u201344:''' Jos\u00e9 Miguel D\u00edez (5)\n:* '''Liga 1949\u201350:''' Julio Ayll\u00f3n (30)<ref>[http://www.tiburones-rojos.com/historia/1943-1953/ La Primera Etapa.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717054344/http://www.tiburones-rojos.com/historia/1943-1953/ |date=2011-07-17 }}</ref>\n:* '''Liga 1989\u201390:''' [[Jorge Comas (footballer)|Jorge Comas]] (26)<ref>[http://www.tiburones-rojos.com/historia/1989-1998/ La Tercera Etapa.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100924212542/http://www.tiburones-rojos.com/historia/1989-1998/ |date=2010-09-24 }}</ref>\n\n* Top Goalscorer: 1969 Jalabea\u00f1os 69 goals\n\n==Players==\n\n===First-team squad===\n{{Updated|30 July 2019}}<ref>http://www.ligamx.net/cancha/club/3107/veracruz</ref>\n<!----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n  -- DO NOT ADD new players before their signing is officially announced by the club.\n  -- !!!!!!!!!!!!DO NOT ASSIGN UNREFERENCED JERSEYS NUMBERS!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!! \n  --!!!!!!!!!!!!!DO NOT predict what a jersey number will be!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!\n  \u2013 ONLY assign jersey numbers when the club or league officially has it on their official website.\n  \u2013 Players with international caps should NOT be bolded \u2013 as per Wikipedia:WikiProject_Football/Clubs\n  \u2013 This is Wikipedia, NOT a football gazette.\n  \u2013 Any unconfirmed and unsourced signing/transfer WILL BE reverted at sight. \n  \u2013 Thank You in advance.\n  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->\n===Reserve teams===\n{{Main|Tiburones Rojos de Veracruz Reserves and Academy|l1=Veracruz Reserves and Academy}}\n\n;[[Albinegros de Orizaba]]\n:Reserve team that plays in the [[Liga Premier de M\u00e9xico|Liga Premier]] in the third level of the Mexican league system.\n\n==Managers==\n{{col-begin-small}}\n{{col-2}}\n* {{flagicon|Spain}} [[Joaqu\u00edn Urquiaga]] (1947\u201348)\n* {{flagicon|Yugoslavia}} [[Bora Milutinovi\u0107|Velibor \"Bora\" Milutinovi\u0107]] (July 1, 1988\u201388)\n* {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Eduardo Antunes Coimbra|Edu Antunes]] (1991)\n* {{flagicon|Chile}} [[Carlos Reinoso]] (1992\u201394)\n* {{flagicon|Peru}} [[Miguel Company]] (July 1, 1993\u2013Dec 31, 1993)\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Tom\u00e1s Boy]] (Sept 23, 1995\u2013June 30, 1996)\n* {{flagicon|Argentina}} [[Luis Manuel Blanco]] (July 1, 1997 \u2013 June 30, 1998)\n* {{flagicon|Uruguay}} [[H\u00e9ctor Hugo Eugui]] (1999)\n* {{flagicon|Bolivia}} [[Carlos Trucco]] (2000)\n* {{flagicon|Argentina}} [[Pablo Centrone]] (2001)\n* {{flagicon|Uruguay}} [[Hugo Fern\u00e1ndez]] (2002)\n* {{flagicon|Israel}} [[Daniel Brailovsky]] (Sept 27, 2002\u2013Dec 31, 2002)\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Daniel Guzm\u00e1n]] (Jan 1, 2003\u2013March 14, 2004)\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Tom\u00e1s Boy]] (March 20, 2004 \u2013 June 30, 2004)\n* {{flagicon|Uruguay}} [[Wilson Graniolatti]] (July 1, 2004\u2013Feb 28, 2005)\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[V\u00edctor Manuel Vucetich]] (March 4, 2005 \u2013 June 30, 2005)\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Alfredo Tena]] (Jan 1, 2006\u2013Feb 14, 2006)\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[V\u00edctor Manuel Vucetich]] (March 3, 2006\u2013Sept 3, 2006)\n* {{flagicon|Argentina}} [[Pedro Monz\u00f3n]] (Sept 7, 2006\u2013Feb 16, 2007)\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Carlos Barra]] ''(interim)'' (Feb 15, 2007\u2013Feb 19, 2007)\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} Emilio Gallegos S\u00e1nchez (Feb 22, 2007\u2013March 11, 2007)\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Alejandro Dom\u00ednguez (Mexican footballer)|Alejandro Dom\u00ednguez]] ''(interim)'' (March 13, 2007 \u2013 March 17, 2007)\n{{col-2}}\n* {{flagicon|Uruguay}} [[An\u00edbal Ruiz]] (March 15, 2007 \u2013 June 30, 2007)\n* {{flagicon|Argentina}} [[Nery Pumpido]] (July 1, 2007\u2013Oct 6, 2007)\n* {{flagicon|Argentina}} [[Antonio Mohamed]] (Sept 4, 2007\u2013Jan 26, 2008)\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Miguel Herrera]] (Jan 31, 2008\u2013June 30, 2008)\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Pablo Luna (footballer)|Pablo Luna]] (July 1, 2008\u2013Aug 31, 2008)\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Sergio Ordu\u00f1a]] (Sept 8, 2008\u2013March 22, 2009)\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Luis Flores (footballer)|Luis Flores]] (April 16, 2009 \u2013 June 30, 2009)\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Joaqu\u00edn del Olmo]] (July 1, 2009\u2013Feb 15, 2010)\n* {{flagicon|Argentina}} [[Jorge Almiron]] (Feb 17, 2010\u2013March 29, 2010)\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Sergio Bueno]] (July 1, 2010\u2013Sept 23, 2010)\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Carlos Turrubiates]] (Sept 24, 2010\u2013Dec 31, 2010)\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Omar Arellano Nu\u00f1o]] (Jan 1, 2011\u2013June 30, 2011)\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Daniel Guzm\u00e1n]] (July 1, 2011\u2013Feb 12, 2012)\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Joaqu\u00edn del Olmo]] (Feb 23, 2012\u2013June 30, 2012)\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[David Pati\u00f1o]] (July 1, 2012\u2013Sept 24, 2012)\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Ignacio Rodr\u00edguez (footballer)|Ignacio Rodr\u00edguez]] (Sept 27, 2012\u2013Dec 31, 2012)\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Miguel de Jes\u00fas Fuentes|Miguel Fuentes]] (Dec 22, 2012\u2013June 30, 2013)\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Juan Antonio Luna]] (July 1, 2013\u2013Feb 9, 2014)\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Jos\u00e9 Luis S\u00e1nchez Sol\u00e1]] (Feb 11, 2014\u201314)\n* {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Crist\u00f3bal Ortega]] (May 26, 2014\u20131?)\n* {{flagicon|Chile}} [[Carlos Reinoso]] (2014\u20132017)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Association football|Mexico}}\n* {{in lang|es}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20040818052416/http://www.tiburones-rojos.com/ Official website]\n{{commons category|position=left|Tiburones Rojos de Veracruz}}\n\n{{C.D. Veracruz}}\n\n[[Category:C.D. Veracruz| ]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Veracruz]]\n[[Category:Veracruz (city)]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1943]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs disestablished in 2019]]\n[[Category:1943 establishments in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Ascenso MX teams]]\n[[Category:Liga MX teams]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the men's football club|the women's football club|C.D. Veracruz (women)}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{more citations needed|date=September 2014}}\n{{Update|date=January 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| nickname = ''Los Tiburones Rojos'' (the red sharks)<br>''Los Escualos'' (The Sharks)<br>''El Tibur\u00f3n (The Shark)''\n| ground = [[Estadio Luis \"Pirata\" Fuente]]<br>[[Boca del R\u00edo, Veracruz|Boca del R\u00edo]], [[Veracruz]], [[Mexico]]\n| capacity = 28,703\n| season =\n| current = \n| clubname = Veracruz\n| fullname = Club Deportivo Veracruz\n| image = CD Veracruz logo.svg\n| image_size = 200px\n| founded = {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|1943|04|09}}\n| dissolved = {{Start date and age|2019|12|18|df=yes}}\n| owner = \n| chairman = \n| manager = \n| league = \n| position = \n| website = http://clubtiburonesrojos.mx/\n| pattern_la1 = _veracruz1920h\n| pattern_b1 = _veracruz1920h\n| pattern_ra1 = _veracruz1920h\n| pattern_sh1 = _veracruz1920h\n| pattern_so1 = _veracruz1920h\n| leftarm1 = FFFFFF\n| body1 = FFFFFF\n| rightarm1 = FFFFFF\n| shorts1 = FFFFFF\n| socks1 = 000060\n| pattern_la2 = _veracruz1920a\n| pattern_b2 = _veracruz1920a\n| pattern_ra2 = _veracruz1920a\n| pattern_sh2 = _veracruz1920a\n| pattern_so2 = _veracruz1920a\n| leftarm2 = FFFFFF\n| body2 = FFFFFF\n| rightarm2 = FFFFFF\n| shorts2 = FFFFFF\n| socks2 = 000060\n| pattern_la3 = _veracruz1920t\n| pattern_b3 = _veracruz1920t\n| pattern_ra3 = _veracruz1920t\n| pattern_sh3 = _veracruz1920t\n| pattern_so3 = _veracruz1920t\n}}\n\n'''Club Deportivo Veracruz''', commonly known as '''Tiburones Rojos de Veracruz''', was a Mexican professional [[Association football|football]] club based in the city of [[Veracruz, Veracruz|Veracruz]]. ''El Aston'' was founded in 1943, and played in the [[Liga MX]] of Mexico. Their nickname, \"Tiburones Rojos\", means red sharks. \n\nIn December 2019, the [[Mexican Football Federation]] announced the disaffiliation of Veracruz from Liga MX due to economic debts with first team players, its youth system, and the league.<ref> http://ligamx.net/cancha/detallenoticia/32956/se-revoca-certificado-de-afiliacion-al-club-tiburones-rojos-de-veracruz</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe club was founded around April 1943 under the name of '''Club Deportivo Veracruz''' after two clubs from the city state of [[Veracruz]], [[Iberia de C\u00f3rdoba]] and [[Veracruz Sporting Club]], merged in order to join the [[Mexican Primera Divisi\u00f3n|Mexican First Division]]. At the time, both clubs played in Liga Veracruzana, an amateur league in Veracruz. These two clubs had dominated the [[Liga Amateur de Veracruz]], winning 21 titles combined. Each of these clubs had a short stay in the [[Primera Fuerza]] \u2013 a now defunct amateur football league in [[Mexico City]] \u2013 in the early 1920s but due to the distance, the clubs generally played in the local league which was less competitive. The club kept the [[Veracruz Sporting Club]] colors, red and black, which they used in the early part of its existence and a few years later would switch the black to white, keeping red as the club's main shirt color. In their first year the club played in [[Parque Deportivo Veracruzano]] sharing the field with baseball club [[Rojos del \u00c1guila de Veracruz]]. The club's nickname was given by Manuel Seyde who had also help merge the two clubs. The club had the honor of having been one of the first clubs to play in the professional league as well as having been the first club not from [[Mexico City]] to win the tournament. Among other records the club holds is most relegations (four times) including being relegated in 2008 by its hated rival [[Puebla F.C.|Puebla]] who had just been promoted the year before. The club has played in the [[Liga de Ascenso]] ever since, coming close to promotion a couple of times but falling short each time.\n\nThe club played its first game in the 1943\u201344 [[Copa M\u00e9xico]] tournament against [[Atlante F.C.|Atlante]] who beat them 5\u20131. The club's first goal was scored by Manuel Rodr\u00edguez Angues, nicknamed as Manol\u00edn.\n\nIn their 1945\u201346 league Veracruz played 18 games with a streak of 14 wins and 4 draws. Veracruz also won their first title in that year. In the season 1947\u201348 they won their first Mexican Cup by beating the Chivas 3\u20131. Soon Veracruz won their second title, in the 1949\u201350 season, with the most overwhelming victory in the history of Mexican football, beating Monterrey, 14\u20130.\n\nYears later Veracruz acquired famous players such as [[Ren\u00e9 Higuita]], [[Braulio Luna]], [[Adolfo R\u00edos]], [[Luis Hern\u00e1ndez (footballer)|Luis Hern\u00e1ndez]], [[Fernando Arce]], [[Alfredo Tena]] and others. After being relegated to the Primera Divisi\u00f3n A Veracruz came back in 2002 after being declared Primera Divisi\u00f3n A champions and finished 11th place in the Summer of 2002. The Apertura 2004 season had been one of the best for Veracruz as they finished 1st place thanks to new signings such as [[Cuauht\u00e9moc Blanco]], [[Christian Gim\u00e9nez (1981)|Christian Gim\u00e9nez]], [[Kl\u00e9ber Boas]] and others. Veracruz has had 59 managers so far, as of 2008. On the night of Friday April 25, 2008 at Luis \"Pirata\" Fuente stadium (Home of the Tiburones Rojos de Veracruz), [[Club Universidad Nacional|UNAM]] defeated Veracruz with a final score of 4\u20132, sending Veracruz to the [[Primera Divisi\u00f3n A|Primera A]] division league. Veracruz was officially relegated from the Mexican Primera Divisi\u00f3n league on the night of Friday May 2, 2008 in the final match of the regular season against Tecos UAG ending in a 0\u20130 draw.\n\n===First title===\n[[File:1945 Veracruz FC.png|thumb|right|1945\u201346 championship club.]]\nIn the club's third year of existence in the 1945\u201346 tournament, the club went on to win 18 games with a record of 14 wins and 4 draws, managing to win 8 straight. The club scored 105 goals that year, leading the club in scoring was the Argentine Jorge Enrico followed by Raimundo Gonzalez with 24. [[Luis de la Fuente (Mexican footballer)|Luis de la Fuente]] was considered the club's best player because of his unique playing style.\n\nIt was on 2 June 1946, in the second to last round of the tournament in the ''Parque Asturias'' in Mexico City, home of [[Real Club Espa\u00f1a]] where the club won 2\u20133 and so were able to claim themselves champions for the first time. With goals scored by Jos\u00e9 Valdivia, [[Luis de la Fuente (Mexican footballer)|Luis de la Fuente]] and Raimundo Gonzalez, they ended a 26-year streak of the tournament being won by a club from [[Mexico City]]. That same year the club went on to lose the [[Campe\u00f3n de Campeones]] title against [[Club Atlas|Atlas]].\n\n===First Copa M\u00e9xico title===\nIn the 1947\u201348 [[Copa M\u00e9xico]] tournament, with the departure of the club's best players (the [[Argentine]] Jorge Enrico along with other good players such as Lazcano and Pachuco Dur\u00e1n, and maybe the club's most important trainer, Palomini) the still club managed to win its first Copa M\u00e9xico. The final was played against [[C.D. Guadalajara|Guadalajara]] with a final score of 3\u20131 under the management of the [[Spaniard]] Joaquin Urquiaga. That is the only cup to date the club has won, finishing runner-up 3 times: in 1949\u201350, 1967\u201368 and 1994\u201395.\n\n===Second title===\n\nIn the 1949\u201350 tournament the club managed to win its last [[Mexican Primera Divisi\u00f3n]] title till date. The club started off that year with a rejuvenated squad led by Juan Luque de Serrallonga who had just come from a stay with the [[Mexico national football team]] the year before. This year is also remembered because the club had its first goal scoring champion: the [[Peruvian]] Julio Ayllon, also known as El Negro, black promotional football players in Mexico being uncommon at that time; Julio went on to score 30 goals that year.\n\n===The end of a Golden Era===\nThe club welcomed the new decade with the start of the end of its golden age. The 1950\u201351 tournament became the first losing year due to economical problems the club faced under the ownership of Miguel Alem\u00e1n Valdez and governor of the state Marco Antonio Mu\u00f1oz.\n\nThe worst season came in the 1951\u201352 tournament after a long relegation fight that came down to the end against [[Club Am\u00e9rica]]; they lost and were relegated for the first time in history to the newly created [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico]]. That year the club finished with a record of 3 wins, 6 draws, and 13 losses allowing 54 goals and only scoring 22 for a total of 12 points, just 3 behind Club Am\u00e9rica (who kept the category and is one of two clubs that has never been relegated since the professionalization of the sport in Mexico).\n\nIn the 1952\u201353 tournament, playing in the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico]], the club finished the year just one point away from been promoted behind [[Deportivo Toluca F.C.|Toluca]], who has played in the first division ever since. After that disappointing year almost all the players left the club following the 1953 cup tournament. As a result, the leagues decided to disband the club.\n\n===Return 1960s\u20131970s===\nIn 1961, thanks to a group of supporters, they established a [[patronage]] in which Jos\u00e9 Lajud Kuri was named president and so revived the club in order to take part in the 1961\u201362 [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico]] tournament. The first couple of years were mediocre and they didn't have any success.\n\nIn 1964 the club was presented with an opportunity to be promoted after the league decided to increase the number of clubs from 14 to 16. That year, the worst first division club, [[Nacional de Guadalajara]], played a promotional playoff tournament against [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico]] [[Petroleros de Ciudad Madero]]. [[Poza Rica]] and [[Veracruz]] had finished 2nd, 3rd and 4th (not counting [[Cruz Azul]] who had earn an automatic promotion after winning the tournament). That tournament ended with [[Nacional de Guadalajara]] and Veracruz earning first and second with [[Petroleros de Ciudad Madero]] third and [[Poza Rica]] fourth. The club had returned to the first division after 12 years of bitter, bitter waiting.\n\nIn the 1964\u201365 first division tournament the club played their first game on June 7, 1964 against [[Monarcas Morelia|Atletico Morelia]] in the city of [[Morelia]] in a 3\u20133 draw. The club's first goal since coming back was scored by Jesus Mercado. That year the club had a record of 10 wins, 8 draws, and 12 defeats; they scored 41 and allowed 44 for a total of 28 points and fishing 10 overall in the league. Their best game was played in the 8th round when they defeated [[Zacatepec]] 5\u20131. In 1978\u201379 the club was relegated for the second time after losing 22 games allowing 83 goals and finishing last in the competition. One thing to mention is that the club had five different trainers that year. One week before their last game in the first division the club secured their relegation after losing, 5\u20132, against [[Club Universidad de Guadalajara]] in the city of [[Guadalajara]]. The last game the club played in that tournament was against [[Tigres de la UANL]] one June 3, 1979, at home where they had a draw of 1\u20131 and so ended their second stay in the first division while ending another decade.\n\n===1980s===\nThe club started the 1980s in the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico]] . After the 1983\u201384 tournament the club was sold to the city of [[Yucat\u00e1n (state)|Yucat\u00e1n]] where it became [[Venados de Yucat\u00e1n]]. This club lasted a couple years before folding in 1998.\n\nAfter several years of not having a football club representing the state of Veracruz, various attempts were made in order revive the club. One such was to buy the [[\u00c1ngeles de Puebla]] franchise which at the time was on sale due to the lack of supporters. The club had been in the same city as [[Puebla F.C.|Puebla]] who had won two league titles and 2 [[Copa M\u00e9xico]] titles in the 1980s. But in 1989, a group of local businessmen along with funding by the governor of the city of Veracruz bought the newly promoted club [[Potros Neza]] which at the time was affiliated with first division club [[Atlante F.C.|Atlante]]. The club played their first tournament game that same year and lost to Puebla under the management of H\u00e9ctor Sanabria. That year the club finished 5th in group 4 with a total of 34 - nonetheless the club managed to win over supporters by been a club that played with a lot of heart.{{Clarify|reason=vague|date=February 2017}} Players such as Davidovich, Jos\u00e9 Lu\u00eds Marroqu\u00edn, Casta\u00f1on, Salcedo, Pascual Ram\u00edrez, Jardon [[Eduardo Rergis]], Eduardo Moses, [[Omar Palma]], and [[Jorge Comas (footballer)|Jorge Comas]] stood out. That year is remembered as La Tiburomania because no matter where the club played it always had a great deal{{Clarify|reason=vague|date=February 2017}} of support no matter the distance. The club return started a euphoria in the city in the 1989\u201390 tournament when the club had 19 straight sell-outs. It all came to a climax when the club played top club [[Club Am\u00e9rica]] in the [[Estadio Azteca]] where 50,000 Veracruz supporters poured into a stadium with a capacity of 114,000 and they set a record for the most supports attending an away game. That game ended in a 3\u20135 win for the home team in a controversial match refereed by Javier Castellanos.\n\nThat same year there was a four-way special tournament inviting Brazilian club [[Botafogo de Futebol e Regatas|Botafogo]], Spanish club [[Real Madrid]] and local club [[Club Universidad Nacional|UNAM]]. [[Botafogo de Futebol e Regatas|Botafogo]] ended up taking home the cup but the fans remember this tournament because the club beat [[Real Madrid]], 4\u20132, with a goal by the Argentine [[Omar Palma]].\n\n===1990s===\n{{Unreferenced section|date=February 2017}}\nThe 1990s began with a group of players and a fan base which became known as La Tiburomaniam who cheer own fan favorite players [[Jorge Comas (footballer)|Jorge Comas]] [[Adolfo R\u00edos]], [[Joaqu\u00edn Del Olmo]], Octavio Becerril, Pascual Ram\u00edrez, [[Jos\u00e9 Lu\u00eds Gonz\u00e1lez China]] under management of the Brazilian Edu. The club failed to qualify to the play-offs after a long battle for 2nd place in group 3 against [[Cruz Azul]].\n\nIn the 1991\u201392 tournament the club give its supporters something to cheer for after a bad start of the tournament which caused the existed of them club taker [[\u00c1ngel L\u00f3pez (footballer)|Angel Lopez]] who was replaced by [[Roberto Matosas]]. After the change of trainer the club had a much better tournament which qualified the club to a knockout play-off series against [[Correcaminos UAT]] which they won, 4\u20133, which they handed done since the club was reform in 1970. The club faced [[Necaxa]] in quarterfinals where they lost, 6\u20132.\n\nIn the 1993\u201394 the club celebrated its 50 anniversary with a special ceremony prior to the tournament where former club greats reunited to play a special match. That preseason the club signed former greats [[Carlos Poblete (footballer)|Carlos Poblete]] and [[Rub\u00e9n Omar Romano]]. That year is also remembered for that great friendly match the club had against [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]].\n\nIn the 1994\u201395 tournament under the management of [[Anibal Ruiz]] who with a peculiar{{Clarify|reason=vague|date=February 2017}} defensive style of coaching made the fans lose interest in the club nonetheless the club qualified to play a knock-out match against its hated rival [[Puebla F.C.|Puebla]] who advanced to the quarterfinals after a 1\u20131 draw moving on due to a better position in the league. The club came close that year to winning the 1994\u201395 Copa M\u00e9xico title after beating [[Irapuato FC|Irapuato]], [[Estudiantes Tecos]] and [[Club Santos Laguna|Santos Laguna]] in that order facing [[Club Necaxa|Necaxa]] in the final match that took place in neutral ground in the [[Estadio Cuauht\u00e9moc]] in the city of [[Puebla (city)|Puebla]] where the club fell 2\u20130. In 1995 the club was sold to local TV network [[Televisa]] who brought in better playgoers to the club reviving once again the hopes of the supporters.\n\nIn the 1996\u201397 the new owners signed [[Jos\u00e9 Mari Bakero]] who had just finished a long career with Spanish giant [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] along with key players from the Colombian national team [[Leonel \u00c1lvarez (footballer, born 1965)|Leonel \u00c1lvarez]], [[Iv\u00e1n Valenciano]], [[Alexis Mendoza]] mating important players and fan favorite goalkeeper [[Adolfo R\u00edos]]. With the hype of the club's new players many gave the club a chance of taking the league title but after a tournament field with injuries and with a divided locker-room the club managed to gain only 9 points and finished last leaving the club in relegation problems for the nest campaign.\n\nIn the 1997\u201398 tournament the club let go most of the players bringing in the international known goalkeeper [[Ren\u00e9 Higuita]] along with players that were unknown in the league in order to avoid their 3rd relegation. With lack of experience the players had the club ended that tournament with a record of 3 wins, 5 draws losing 9 games for a total of 14 points and so once selling their 3rd relegation in club history.\n\nIn the invierno del 98 playing now in the [[Liga de Ascenso|Primera A]] the club started their journey to return once again to the top division hiring Juan Manuel Alvarez who had achieve this task before with [[Club Celaya]] a few years back. With the supports still hurt by the relegation at mid tournament Juan Manuel Alvarez was replaced by \"El Turco\" Aude coach who had lots of experience in the league and managed to rally the players reaching the semi-finals that year losing the series to [[Venados de Yucat\u00e1n]].\n\nIn 1999 the club was sold to city of [[Veracruz]] along with local business owners. The club won of its worst tournaments in its history that inverno 99 with a club mostly formed by veteran players along with young experienced players. In that tournament the club failed to qualify for the play-offs and the promotion seemed impossible each day \u2013 and that is how the club ended that decade with some strong clubs in the early part of the decade and with the club's third relation at the end of it.\n\n===2000s===\n{{Unreferenced section|date=February 2017}}\nIn the 2000\u201301 tournament the club finally lived up to its expectation becoming a competitive club in the [[Liga de Ascenso|Primera A]] the first have under the management of [[Carlos Trucco]] and [[Roberto Saporiti]] in other half, these two managers went on to win several games that would qualify them to the playoff where they were eliminated but had revived interest in the locals. At the end of that tournament the first division expanded from 18 to 20 which promoted two clubs that year. [[C.F. La Piedad|La Piedad]] was promoted after winning the Verano 2001 [[Liga de Ascenso|Primera A]] tournament and going on to win the Promotion match against [[Toros Neza]]. A promotion series was played between [[Atlante F.C.|Atlante]] who had the worst relegation percentage against the club that had gain the most points in the [[Liga de Ascenso|Primera A]] that been [[Veracruz]]. A second promotion match was played between those two clubs the first match was played in jam packed [[Estadio Luis de la Fuente]] in Veracruz in match that ended in a 0\u20130 draw. The second match was played in the [[Estadio Azteca]] where [[Atlante F.C.|Atlante]] defeated the Veracruz, 4\u20131, and remained in the top division.\n\n===2002 promotion===\nIn 2002 they were promoted to the [[Mexican Primera Divisi\u00f3n]] following their play-off victory against [[Club L\u00e9on|L\u00e9on]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesm/mex02.html|title=Mexico 2001/02|last=Jos\u00e9 de Jesus Mora Rivera and Daniel Dalence Garcia|date=22 January 2009|publisher=RSSSF|accessdate=4 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n===2008 relegation===\nIn the 2007 Aperture the club finished second to last in the percentage table just above [[Puebla F.C.|Puebla]] and below [[Tigres UANL]] with a percentage of 1.0706.\n\nIn the [[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico Clausura 2008]] the club once again had a bad year with a record of 4 wins, 5 draws and losing 8 for a total of 17 points finishing 16 in the league. The club shed its relegation after losing at home against their direct rivals in the relegation fight Puebla with a score of 2\u20130. The club's relegation was made official in the following match against [[Club Universidad Nacional|UNAM]] at home losing 4\u20132 and setting a new league record for a relegation with 4.\n\nThe club played in the [[Liga de Ascenso]] since the Apertura 2008 and came close several times but always coming short.\n\n===2011 Disaffiliation===\nOn June 3, 2011, the [[Mexican Football Federation|FMF]] disaffiliated the Tiburones Rojos because of a failure of payments to the FMF.\n\nThe Federacion Mexicana de Futbol Asociacion, AC informs that the Ordinary General Assembly at its meeting today, once it analyzed the situation of Representaciones Soha, Inc., SA de CV, (Club Veracruz and / or Club Tiburones Rojos de Veracruz), a member of the Liga de Ascenso, The Mexican Football Federation, AC unanimously decided, with its power under Articles 17, 25 and other related and applicable Statute of the FMF, revoke the Certificate of Membership and consequently disaffiliate such an entity, for failing to meet its financial obligations to FMF and its affiliates.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.femexfut.org.mx/portalv2/aspx/WEB_DetalleNoticia.aspx?pnIDNtca=32942 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-08-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120804055007/http://www.femexfut.org.mx/portalv2/aspx/WEB_DetalleNoticia.aspx?pnIDNtca=32942 |archivedate=2012-08-04 }}</ref>\n\nAfter that announcement, it was accorded between Veracruz and [[Albinegros de Orizaba]] to unify their teams after the debts the team had.\n\n===2013 Club Change===\nClub San Luis was relocated to Tuxtla Gutierrez, [[Chiapas F.C.|Chiapas]] to play at the Estadio V\u00edctor Manuel Reyna, under the name Chiapas Football Club. Club La Piedad was relocated to the state of Veracruz to play at the Estadio Luis \"Pirata\" Fuente, under the name of [[CD Veracruz|Veracruz]].\n\n===2019 disaffiliation===\nAfter enduring a 41-game winless run dating from September 2018 to October 2019, multiple reports of players not receiving payment, an in-game protest against [[Tigres UANL]] in the 2019 Apertura, and repeated discontent with owner Fidel Kurri, the FMF officially [https://www.espn.com/soccer/veracruz/story/4006415/worst-club-veracruz-gets-liga-mx-boot-amid-struggles disaffiliated Veracruz] from Liga MX following the 2019 Apertura. Their players became free agents, free to sign with any club, and their [[C.D. Veracruz (women)|women's team]] was also kicked out of the [[Liga MX Femenil]]. All other branches of the club, including its academies and reserves, dissolved as well. As a result, Liga MX began its 2020 Clausura with only 18 teams.\n\n==Rivalries==\n{{Main|El Cl\u00e1sico Del Sur}}\nThe club had a long-standing rivalry with [[Puebla F.C.|Puebla]]. This rivalry dated back to the amateur era from the early 1930s, before both clubs had been admitted into the professional division in 1944.\n\nIn all Puebla and [[CD Veracruz|Veracruz]] played 68 official matches including league and [[Copa M\u00e9xico]]. Puebla had the best record with 30 wins 15 draws.\n\n==Past sponsors==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Manufacturer\n!Main Sponsor\n!Other Sponsors\n|-\n|1989\u201394\n|Pony\n|\n|\n|-\n|1994\u201395\n|[[Adidas]]\n|[[Coca-Cola]]\n|\n|-\n|1995\u201397\n|[[Umbro]]\n|[[Coca-Cola]]\n|Superior\n|-\n|1998\u201308\n|[[Atletica]]\n|[[Banco Azteca]]\n|Cerveza Sol, [[Grupo Gigante]], Pegaso, [[Grupo Bimbo|Bimbo]]\n|-\n|2009\u201310\n|[[Joma]]\n||The phone house\n||Cerveza Sol, Tele-Ver\n|-\n|2010\u201311\n|Nike\n||The phone house\n||Cerveza Sol, Tele-Ver\n|-\n|2011\u201312\n|[[Nike, Inc.|Nike]]\n||[[Chedraui]]\n||Cerveza Sol, Tele-Ver\n|-\n|2013\u20132014\n|Kappa\n|Winpot Casino\n|[[Pascual Boing|Boing]], Tele-Ver, [[Tecate]]\n|-\n|2014\u201319\n|Charly\n|Winpot Casino\n|[[Pascual Boing|Boing]], ADO, [[Cuauht\u00e9moc Moctezuma Brewery|Tecate]]\n|}\n\n===First kit evolution===\n{|\n|-\n|\n{{Football kit |\npattern_la = |\npattern_b  = _vera1|\npattern_ra = |\nleftarm  = FF0000|\nbody     = 0000FF|\nrightarm    = FF0000|\nshorts     = 000040 |\nsocks      = 000040|\ntitle      = 1943\n}}\n|\n{{Football kit |\npattern_la = |\npattern_b = _|\npattern_ra = |\nleftarm = FF0000 |\nbody = FF0000|\nrightarm = FF0000 |\nshorts = black |\nsocks = FF0000 |\ntitle = 1950\n}}\n|\n{{Football kit |\npattern_la = |\npattern_b =  |\npattern_ra = |\nleftarm = FF0000 |\nbody = FF0000|\nrightarm =FF0000 |\nshorts = 000040|\nsocks = FF0000 |\ntitle = 1960\n}}\n|\n{{Football kit |\npattern_la = |\npattern_b =_vera2 |\npattern_ra = |\nleftarm = FF0000 |\nbody = 000099 |\nrightarm = FF0000 |\nshorts = 000040 |\nsocks = 000040 |\ntitle = 1978\n}}\n|\n{{Football kit |\npattern_la = |\npattern_b =_vera3 |\npattern_ra = |\nleftarm = FF0000 |\nbody = 000099 |\nrightarm = FF0000 |\nshorts = 000040 |\nsocks = 000040 |\ntitle = 1990\n}}\n|\n{{Football kit |\npattern_la = |\npattern_b =_vera4 |\npattern_ra = |\nleftarm = FF0000 |\nbody = 000000 |\nrightarm = FF0000 |\nshorts = 000040 |\nsocks =000040 |\ntitle = 1995\n}}\n|\n{{Football kit |\npattern_la = 000040 |\npattern_b =_vera5 |\npattern_ra = 000040 |\nleftarm = FF0000 |\nbody = 000009 |\nrightarm = FF0000 |\nshorts = F00000|\nsocks =000040 |\ntitle = 2001\n}}\n|\n{{Football kit |\npattern_la = |\npattern_b =_vera6 |\npattern_ra = |\nleftarm = FF0000 |\nbody = 000099 |\nrightarm = FF0000 |\nshorts = FF0000|\nsocks =FF0000 |\ntitle =2008\n}}\n|\n{{Football kit |\npattern_la =_tiburonesrojos1213L |\npattern_b =_Tiburonesrojos1213L |\npattern_ra =_tiburonesrojos1213L |\npattern_sh1=_veracruzshortkappa|\nleftarm = FF0000 |\nbody = FF0000 |\nrightarm = FF0000 |\nshorts = 000040|\nsocks =000040 |\ntitle =2013\n}}\n|}\n\n==Honors==\n* '''[[Mexican Primera Divisi\u00f3n|Primera Divisi\u00f3n]]: 2'''\n::1945\u201346, 1949\u201350\n* '''[[Primera Divisi\u00f3n A]]: 1'''\n::2001\n* '''[[Copa M\u00e9xico]]/[[Copa MX]]: 2'''\n::1947\u201348, [[Clausura 2016 Copa MX|2016 Clausura]]\n\n==Record==\n\n===Year-by-Year===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Season\n!Pyramid Level\n!Regular Season 1\n!Playoffs 1\n!Regular Season 2\n!Playoffs 2\n![[Copa M\u00e9xico]]\n![[CONCACAF Champions League|CONCACAF]]\n|-\n|2001\u201302\n|2 and [[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico Verano 2002|1]]\n|4th\n|Champions\n|11th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|No Longer played\n|''Did not qualify''\n|-\n|2002\u201303\n|[[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico Clausura 2003|1]]\n|18th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|7th\n|''Semifinals''\n|No Longer played\n|''Did not qualify''\n|-\n|2003\u201304\n|[[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico Clausura 2004|1]]\n|12th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|20th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|No Longer played\n|''Did not qualify''\n|-\n|2004\u201305\n|[[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico Clausura 2005|1]]\n|1st\n|''Quarter-finals''\n|17th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|No Longer played\n|''Did not qualify''\n|-\n|2005\u201306\n|[[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico Clausura 2006|1]]\n|18th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|16th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|No Longer played\n|''Did not qualify''\n|-\n|2006\u201307\n|[[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico Clausura 2007|1]]\n|9th\n|''Repechaje''\n|18th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|No Longer played\n|''Did not qualify''\n|-\n|2007\u201308\n|[[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico Clausura 2008|1]]\n|13th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|16th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|No Longer played\n|''Did not qualify''\n|-\n|2008\u201309\n||2\n|11th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|3rd\n|''Semi-finals''\n|No Longer played\n|''Did not qualify''\n|-\n|2009\u201310\n|[[2010 Liga de Ascenso Bicentenario|2]]\n|4th\n|''Semi-finals''\n|15th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|No Longer played\n|''Did not qualify''\n|-\n|[[2010-11 Tiburones Rojos de Veracruz season|2010\u201311]]\n|[[2010\u201311 Liga de Ascenso season|2]]\n|5th\n|''Second Place''\n|5th\n|''Disqualified''\n|No Longer played\n|''Did not qualify''\n|-\n|[[2011-12 Tiburones Rojos de Veracruz season|2011\u201312]]\n|[[2011\u201312 Liga de Ascenso season|2]]\n|8th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|13th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|No Longer played\n|''Did not qualify''\n|-\n|[[2012-13 Tiburones Rojos de Veracruz season|2012\u201313]]\n|[[2012\u201313 Ascenso MX season|2]]\n|12th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|4th\n|''Quarter-finals''\n|4th (DNQ)<br>3rd (DNQ)\n|''Did not qualify''\n|-\n|[[2013-14 Tiburones Rojos de Veracruz season|2013\u201314]]\n|[[2013\u201314 Liga MX season|1]]\n|12th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|18th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|3rd (DNQ)<br>1st (Semi-finals)\n|''Did not qualify''\n|-\n|[[2014-15 Tiburones Rojos de Veracruz season|2014\u201315]]\n|[[2014\u201315 Liga MX season|1]]\n|17th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|3rd\n|''Quarter-finals''\n|3rd (DNQ)<br>3rd (DNQ)\n|''Did not qualify''\n|-\n|[[2015-16 Tiburones Rojos de Veracruz season|2015\u201316]]\n|[[2015\u201316 Liga MX season|1]]\n|8th\n|''Quarter-finals''\n|17th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|1st (Quarter-finals)<br>1st (Champions)\n|''Did not qualify''\n|-\n|[[2016-17 Tiburones Rojos de Veracruz season|2016\u201317]]\n|[[2016\u201317 Liga MX season|1]]\n|17th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|13th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|2nd (Round of 16)<br>2nd (DNQ)\n|''Did not qualify''\n|-\n|[[2017-18 Tiburones Rojos de Veracruz season|2017\u201318]]\n|[[2017\u201318 Liga MX season|1]]\n|17th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|16th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|2nd (DNQ)<br>3rd (DNQ)\n|''Did not qualify''\n|-\n|[[2018-19 Tiburones Rojos de Veracruz season|2018\u201319]]\n|[[2018\u201319 Liga MX season|1]]\n|18th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|18th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|3rd (DNQ)<br>1st (Quarter-finals)\n|''Did not qualify''\n|-\n|[[2019-20 Tiburones Rojos de Veracruz season|2019\u201320]]\n|[[2019\u201320 Liga MX season|1]]\n|19th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|Disaffiliated\n|''Did not qualify''\n|2nd (DNQ)\n|''Did not qualify''\n|}\n\n==Club Records==\n* '''Longest undefeated streak:''' 18 (1945\u201346)\n* '''Most game without a draw:''' 19 (Invierno '99)\n* '''Most games without a win:''' 40 (Clausura 2019)\n* '''Longest winning streak:''' 8 (1945\u201346 y Apertura 2004)\n* '''longest draw streak:''' 5 (1990\u201391)\n* '''Longest losing streak:''' 9 (Verano 2002)\n* '''Longest scoring streak:''' 28 (1946\u201347)\n* '''Longest streak without a goal:''' 4 (1970\u201371)\n* '''Longest streak with allowing a goal:''' 4 (1967\u201368 e Invierno 2000)\n* '''Biggest win:''' 14\u20130 May 26, 1946 vs. [[C.F. Monterrey|Monterrey]]\n* '''Biggest loss:''' 9\u20132 April 13, 2019 vs. [[C.F. Pachuca]] Veracruz vs. 0-7 Necaxa\n\n\n===All time top Goalscorers===\n\nThese are the top 10 all time goal scorers in the club history.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090803234542/http://www.tiburones-rojos.com/historia/records/ Clubs Records]</ref>\n\n{| cellpadding=\"3\" cellspacing=\"0\" border=\"1\" style=\"background:#f7f8ff; margin:auto; font-size:95%; border:gray solid 1px; border-collapse:collapse;\"\n|- style=\"background:#ddd; text-align:center; color:black;\"\n!width=\"40\"|Position\n! style=\"width:220px;\"|Player\n! style=\"width:160px;\"|Goals\n! style=\"width:140px;\"|Years\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|1\n|[[File:Flag of Brazil.svg|20px|Brazil]] Mariano Ubiracy\n|98\n|1965\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|2\n|[[File:Flag of Mexico.svg|20px|Argentina]] [[Luis de la Fuente (Mexican footballer)|Luis \"Pirata\" de la Fuente]]\n|83\n|1943\u201352\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|3\n|[[File:Flag of Mexico.svg|20px|Chile]] Raymundo \"Pel\u00f3n\" Gonz\u00e1lez\n|77\n|1986\u201396\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|4\n|[[File:Flag of Argentina.svg|20px|Uruguay]] [[Jorge Comas (footballer)|Jorge Comas]]\n|77\n|1989\u201394\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|5\n|[[File:Flag of Chile.svg|20px|Chile]] Jos\u00e9 Luis \"Loco\" Auss\u00edn\n|65\n|1964-1971\n|- style=