{"title_page": "Medusa (1973 film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Medusa\n| image          = \n| border         = \n| caption        = \n| producer       = [[George Hamilton (actor)|George Hamilton]]\n| director       = [[Gordon Hessler]]\n| writer         = [[Christopher Wicking]]\n| based on       = \n| starring       = [[George Hamilton (actor)|George Hamilton]]<br>[[Luciana Paluzzi]]<br>[[Cameron Mitchell (actor)|Cameron Mitchell]]<br>[[Alana Stewart]]\n| music          = Theodore Roubanis\n| cinematography = Dimitris Papakonstadis\n| editing        = D. Caridis-Fuchs\n| studio         = Roubanis and Company\n| distributor    = American National Enterprises\n| released       = {{Film date|1973|07|23|Italy}}\n| country        = United States\n| runtime        = 103 minutes\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Medusa''''' is a 1973 American [[mystery film]] starring and produced by [[George Hamilton (actor)|George Hamilton]] directed by [[Gordon Hessler]]. It was co written by [[Christopher Wicking]], the last of five collaborations he had with Hessler.<ref>Christopher Wicking\nAnonymous. The Times; London (UK) [London (UK)]01 Nov 2008: 70. </ref> It was Hamilton's second film as producer (the first being ''[[Evel Knievel (1971 film)|Evel Knievel]]'') and was shot in Greece.<ref>Tempo/People: Tower Ticker\nGold, Aaron. Chicago Tribune 18 Nov 1974: b16. </ref>\n\n==Plot==\nA stewardess is murdered by a masked man in Greece. The leading suspects are an American playboy and a gangster.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[George Hamilton (actor)|George Hamilton]] as Jeffrey\n*[[Luciana Paluzzi]] as Sarah\n*[[Cameron Mitchell (actor)|Cameron Mitchell]] as Angelo\n*[[Alana Stewart]] as Eleana\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|tt0070380}}\n*[https://letterboxd.com/film/medusa/ Medusa] at Letterbox DVD\n\n{{Gordon Hessler}}\n[[Category:1973 films]]\n{{thriller-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''''Medusa''''' is a 1973 American [[mystery film]] starring and produced by [[George Hamilton (actor)|George Hamilton]] directed by [[Gordon Hessler]]. It was co written by [[Christopher Wicking]], the last of five collaborations he had with Hessler.<ref>Christopher Wicking\nAnonymous. The Times; London (UK) [London (UK)]01 Nov 2008: 70. </ref> It was Hamilton's second film as producer (the first being ''[[Evel Knievel (1971 film)|Evel Knievel]]'') and was shot in Greece.<ref>Tempo/People: Tower Ticker\nGold, Aaron. Chicago Tribune 18 Nov 1974: b16. </ref>\n==Plot==\nA stewardess is murdered by a masked man in Greece. The leading suspects are an American playboy and a gangster.\n==Cast==\n*[[George Hamilton (actor)|George Hamilton]]\n*[[Luciana Paluzzi]]\n*[[Cameron Mitchell (actor)|Cameron Mitchell]]\n*[[Alana Stewart]]\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|tt0070380}}\n*[https://letterboxd.com/film/medusa/ Medusa] at Letterbox DVD\n{{Gordon Hessler}}\n[[Category:1973 films]]\n{{thriller-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medusa_(1973_film)"}
{"title_page": "Aur\u00e9lien Tach\u00e9", "text_new": "{{short description|French politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{infobox officeholder\n| name        = Aur\u00e9lien Tach\u00e9\n| office      = Member of the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]]<br />for [[Val-d'Oise's 10th constituency]]\n| term_start  = 21 June 2017\n| term_end    =\n| predecessor = Dominique Lefebvre\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1984|05|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Niort]], France\n| nationality = French\n| party       = [[La R\u00e9publique En Marche!]]\n}}\n'''Aur\u00e9lien Tach\u00e9''' (born 26 May 1984) is a French politician of [[La R\u00e9publique En Marche!]] (LREM) who was elected to the [[National Assembly (France)|French National Assembly]] on 18 June 2017, representing the [[Departments of France|department]] of [[Val-d'Oise]].<ref name=\"Bio\">{{Cite web|url=http://elections.interieur.gouv.fr/legislatives-2017/095/09510.html |title=Elections l\u00e9gislatives 2017 |accessdate=30 June 2017 |work=Ministry of the Interior |language=French}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nIn parliament, Tach\u00e9 serves on the Committee on Social Affairs, where was his parliamentary group's coordinator from 2017 until 2018,<ref>Mathilde Siraud (23 January 2018), [https://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/le-scan/coulisses/2018/01/23/25006-20180123ARTFIG00135-richard-ferrand-remanie-le-groupe-lrem-a-l-assemblee.php \u00c0 l'Assembl\u00e9e, Ferrand tente de ressouder les Marcheurs] ''[[Le Figaro]]''.</ref>  and the Finance Committee. In addition to his committee assignments, he is part of the French-Tunisian Parliamentary Friendship Group and the French-Ukrainian Parliamentary Friendship Group.<ref>[http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/deputes/fiche/OMC_PA720952 Aur\u00e9lien Tach\u00e9] [[National Assembly (France)|French National Assembly]].</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\nTach\u00e9 is considered a close ally of [[President of France|President]] [[Emmanuel Macron]].<ref>C\u00e9dric Pietralunga and Alexandre Lemari\u00e9 (20 October 2017), [https://www.lemonde.fr/la-republique-en-marche/article/2017/10/20/enquete-sur-les-snipers-de-la-macronie_5203537_5126036.html La R\u00e9publique en marche: Les snipers de la Macronie] ''[[Le Monde]]''.</ref> \n\nIn May 2018, Tach\u00e9 co-sponsored an initiative in favour of of a bioethics law extending to homosexual and single women free access to [[Assisted reproductive technology|fertility treatments]] such as [[in vitro fertilisation]] (IVF) under France's national health insurance; it was one of Macron's campaign promises and marked the president's first major social reform of his five-year term.<ref>Harriet Agnew (24 September 2019), [https://www.ft.com/content/6b5d2b5e-de11-11e9-b112-9624ec9edc59 France moves to extend IVF to gay and single women] ''[[Financial Times]]''.</ref><ref>[https://www.liberation.fr/debats/2018/05/29/la-pma-pour-toutes-un-acte-d-egalite_1655111 La PMA pour toutes, un acte d\u2019\u00e9galit\u00e9] ''[[Lib\u00e9ration]]'', 29 May 2018.</ref>\n\nIn early 2018, Tach\u00e9 was one of several LREM members who joined an informal parliamentary working group on [[Islam]] set up by [[Florent Boudi\u00e9]] in order to contribute to the government's bill aimed at better organising and supervising the financing of the Muslim faith in France.<ref>Alexandre Lemari\u00e9 (23 November 2018), [https://www.lemonde.fr/politique/article/2018/11/23/des-deputes-la-republique-en-marche-s-attellent-au-sujet-de-l-islam-de-france_5387262_823448.html Des d\u00e9put\u00e9s La R\u00e9publique en marche s\u2019attellent au sujet de l\u2019islam de France] ''[[Le Monde]]''.</ref> In 2019, he was one of five members of the LREM parliamentary group who joined a cross-party initiative to legalize the distribution and use of [[cannabis]].<ref>Harriet Agnew (20 June 2019), [https://www.ft.com/content/df0c4b88-936c-11e9-aea1-2b1d33ac3271 French MPs push to legalise distribution and use of cannabis] ''[[Financial Times]]''.</ref><ref>Marylou Magal (19 June 2019), [https://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/le-scan/les-deputes-lrem-person-et-tache-favorables-a-la-legalisation-du-cannabis-20190619 Les d\u00e9put\u00e9s LREM Person et Tach\u00e9 favorables \u00e0 la l\u00e9galisation du cannabis] ''[[Le Figaro]]''.</ref>\n\nLed by Tach\u00e9, [[Hugues Renson]] and [[Matthieu Orphelin]], a group of around 20 members of the LREM parliamentary group was established in late 2018 with a \"wish to express a humanist, social and ecological sensibility and to better raise citizens' concerns\"; the initiative was widely interpreted as the launch of a left-wing faction within the group.<ref>Mathilde Siraud (20 December 2018), [https://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/2018/12/20/01002-20181220ARTFIG00354-des-deputes-larem-s-organisent-pour-peser.php Des d\u00e9put\u00e9s LaREM s'organisent pour peser] ''[[Le Figaro]]''.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2017 French legislative election]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tache, Aurelien}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Niort]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 15th National Assembly of the French Fifth Republic]]\n[[Category:La R\u00e9publique En Marche politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{infobox officeholder\n| name        = Aur\u00e9lien Tach\u00e9\n| office      = Member of the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]]<br />for [[Val-d'Oise's 10th constituency]]\n| term_start  = 21 June 2017\n| term_end    =\n| predecessor = Dominique Lefebvre\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1984|05|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Niort]], France\n| nationality = French\n| party       = [[La R\u00e9publique En Marche!]]\n}}\n'''Aur\u00e9lien Tach\u00e9''' (born 26 May 1984) is a French politician of [[La R\u00e9publique En Marche!]] (LREM) who was elected to the [[National Assembly (France)|French National Assembly]] on 18 June 2017, representing the [[Departments of France|department]] of [[Val-d'Oise]].<ref name=\"Bio\">{{Cite web|url=http://elections.interieur.gouv.fr/legislatives-2017/095/09510.html |title=Elections l\u00e9gislatives 2017 |accessdate=30 June 2017 |work=Ministry of the Interior |language=French}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nIn parliament, Tach\u00e9 serves on the Committee on Social Affairs, where was his parliamentary group's coordinator from 2017 until 2018,<ref>Mathilde Siraud (23 January 2018), [https://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/le-scan/coulisses/2018/01/23/25006-20180123ARTFIG00135-richard-ferrand-remanie-le-groupe-lrem-a-l-assemblee.php \u00c0 l'Assembl\u00e9e, Ferrand tente de ressouder les Marcheurs] ''[[Le Figaro]]''.</ref>  and the Finance Committee. In addition to his committee assignments, he is part of the French-Tunisian Parliamentary Friendship Group and the French-Ukrainian Parliamentary Friendship Group.<ref>[http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/deputes/fiche/OMC_PA720952 Aur\u00e9lien Tach\u00e9] [[National Assembly (France)|French National Assembly]].</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\nTach\u00e9 is considered a close ally of [[President of France|President]] [[Emmanuel Macron]].<ref>C\u00e9dric Pietralunga and Alexandre Lemari\u00e9 (20 October 2017), [https://www.lemonde.fr/la-republique-en-marche/article/2017/10/20/enquete-sur-les-snipers-de-la-macronie_5203537_5126036.html La R\u00e9publique en marche: Les snipers de la Macronie] ''[[Le Monde]]''.</ref> \n\nIn May 2018, Tach\u00e9 co-sponsored an initiative in favour of of a bioethics law extending to homosexual and single women free access to [[Assisted reproductive technology|fertility treatments]] such as [[in vitro fertilisation]] (IVF) under France's national health insurance; it was one of Macron's campaign promises and marked the president's first major social reform of his five-year term.<ref>Harriet Agnew (September 24, 2019), [https://www.ft.com/content/6b5d2b5e-de11-11e9-b112-9624ec9edc59 France moves to extend IVF to gay and single women] ''[[Financial Times]]''.</ref><ref>[https://www.liberation.fr/debats/2018/05/29/la-pma-pour-toutes-un-acte-d-egalite_1655111 La PMA pour toutes, un acte d\u2019\u00e9galit\u00e9] ''[[Lib\u00e9ration]]'', 29 May 2018.</ref>\n\nIn early 2018, Tach\u00e9 was one of several LREM members who joined an informal parliamentary working group on [[Islam]] set up by [[Florent Boudi\u00e9]] in order to contribute to the government's bill aimed at better organising and supervising the financing of the Muslim faith in France.<ref>Alexandre Lemari\u00e9 (23 November 2018), [https://www.lemonde.fr/politique/article/2018/11/23/des-deputes-la-republique-en-marche-s-attellent-au-sujet-de-l-islam-de-france_5387262_823448.html Des d\u00e9put\u00e9s La R\u00e9publique en marche s\u2019attellent au sujet de l\u2019islam de France] ''[[Le Monde]]''.</ref> In 2019, he was one of five members of the LREM parliamentary group who joined a cross-party initiative to legalize the distribution and use of [[cannabis]].<ref>Harriet Agnew (20 June 2019), [https://www.ft.com/content/df0c4b88-936c-11e9-aea1-2b1d33ac3271 French MPs push to legalise distribution and use of cannabis] ''[[Financial Times]]''.</ref><ref>Marylou Magal (19 June 2019), [https://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/le-scan/les-deputes-lrem-person-et-tache-favorables-a-la-legalisation-du-cannabis-20190619 Les d\u00e9put\u00e9s LREM Person et Tach\u00e9 favorables \u00e0 la l\u00e9galisation du cannabis] ''[[Le Figaro]]''.</ref>\n\nLed by Tach\u00e9, [[Hugues Renson]] and [[Matthieu Orphelin]], a group of around 20 members of the LREM parliamentary group was established in late 2018 with a \"wish to express a humanist, social and ecological sensibility and to better raise citizens' concerns\"; the initiative was widely interpreted as the launch of a left-wing faction within the group.<ref>Mathilde Siraud (20 December 2018), [https://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/2018/12/20/01002-20181220ARTFIG00354-des-deputes-larem-s-organisent-pour-peser.php Des d\u00e9put\u00e9s LaREM s'organisent pour peser] ''[[Le Figaro]]''.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2017 French legislative election]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tache, Aurelien}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Niort]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 15th National Assembly of the French Fifth Republic]]\n[[Category:La R\u00e9publique En Marche politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aur%C3%A9lien_Tach%C3%A9"}
{"title_page": "Aurore Berg\u00e9", "text_new": "{{short description|French politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{infobox officeholder\n| name        = Aurore Berg\u00e9\n| image       = Aurore Berg\u00e9.jpg\n| office      = Member of the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]]<br/>for [[Yvelines]]'s [[Yvelines's 10th constituency|10th]] constituency\n| term_start  = 21 June 2017\n| term_end    =\n| predecessor = [[Jean-Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Poisson]]\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1986|11|13|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Paris]], France\n| nationality = French\n| party       = [[Union for a Popular Movement]] {{small|(2002\u20132015)}}<br/>[[The Republicans (France)|The Republicans]] {{small|(2015\u20132017)}}<br/>[[La R\u00e9publique En Marche!]] {{small|(2017\u2013present)}}\n| alma_mater  = [[Sciences Po]]\n}}\n'''Aurore Berg\u00e9''' (born 13 November 1986) is a French politician who has been serving as a member of the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]] since 2017, representing [[Yvelines's 10th constituency]]. She is considered a close ally of [[President of France|President]] [[Emmanuel Macron]].<ref>C\u00e9dric Pietralunga and Alexandre Lemari\u00e9 (20 October 2017), [https://www.lemonde.fr/la-republique-en-marche/article/2017/10/20/enquete-sur-les-snipers-de-la-macronie_5203537_5126036.html La R\u00e9publique en marche: Les snipers de la Macronie] ''[[Le Monde]]''.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nA native of [[Paris]], Berg\u00e9 studied at [[Sciences Po]]. She became a member of the [[Union for a Popular Movement]] (UMP) in 2002;<ref>[https://www.lejdd.fr/Politique/les-10-deputes-qui-vont-peser-dans-le-quinquennat-3400187 Les 10 d\u00e9put\u00e9s qui vont peser dans le quinquennat] ''[[Le Journal du Dimanche]]'', 1 August 2017.</ref> when the party became [[The Republicans (France)|The Republicans]] (LR) in 2015, she joined it. In the [[2016 The Republicans (France) presidential primary|Republicans' primaries]] ahead of the [[2017 French presidential election|2017 presidential elections]], she campaigned for [[Alain Jupp\u00e9]].<ref>[https://www.lejdd.fr/Politique/les-10-deputes-qui-vont-peser-dans-le-quinquennat-3400187 Les 10 d\u00e9put\u00e9s qui vont peser dans le quinquennat] ''[[Le Journal du Dimanche]]'', 1 August 2017.</ref>\n\nBerg\u00e9 joined [[La R\u00e9publique En Marche!]] in 2017. She has also been a municipal councillor of [[Magny-les-Hameaux]] since the [[2014 French municipal elections|2014 elections]].<ref name=\"Bio\">{{Cite web|url=http://elections.interieur.gouv.fr/legislatives-2017/078/07810.html |title=Elections l\u00e9gislatives 2017 |accessdate=19 June 2017 |work=Ministry of the Interior |language=French}}</ref> In parliament, Berg\u00e9 serves as member of the Committee on Cultural Affairs and Education.<ref>[http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/deputes/fiche/OMC_PA722046 Aurore Berg\u00e9] [[National Assembly (France)|French National Assembly]].</ref>\n\nFrom 2017 until 2019, Berg\u00e9 served as one of her parliamentary group's spokespersons under the leadership of its successive chairmen [[Richard Ferrand]] and [[Gilles Le Gendre]].<ref>Mathilde Siraud (14 January 2019), [https://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/le-scan/coulisses/2019/01/14/25006-20190114ARTFIG00336-le-groupe-larem-a-l-assemblee-muscle-son-equipe-de-porte-paroles.php Le groupe LaREM \u00e0 l'Assembl\u00e9e muscle son \u00e9quipe de porte-parole] ''[[Le Figaro]]''.</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\nIn the [[2012 Union for a Popular Movement leadership election]], Berg\u00e9 supported [[Fran\u00e7ois Fillon]] as the party's leader.<ref>Nolwenn Le Blevennec (18 November 2016), [https://www.nouvelobs.com/rue89/rue89-politique/20131028.RUE9655/aurore-berge-26-ans-la-candidate-ump-qui-a-tout-pour-plaire-a-la-gauche.html Aurore Berg\u00e9, 26 ans, la candidate UMP qui a tout pour plaire \u00e0 la gauche] ''[[L'Obs|Le Nouvel Observateur]]''.</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, following the appointment of [[Fran\u00e7ois de Rugy]] to the government, Berg\u00e9 supported the candidacy of [[Richard Ferrand]] for the presidency of the National Assembly.<ref>Julie Cloris (9 September 2018), [http://www.leparisien.fr/politique/duel-ferrand-pompili-pour-presider-l-assemblee-qui-soutient-qui-09-09-2018-7881792.php Duel Ferrand-Pompili pour pr\u00e9sider l\u2019Assembl\u00e9e : qui soutient qui ?] ''[[Le Parisien]]''.</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Berg\u00e9 led (with [[Guillaume Chiche]]) a group of LREM members who advocated for of a bioethics law extending to homosexual and single women free access to [[Assisted reproductive technology|fertility treatments]] such as [[in vitro fertilisation]] (IVF) under France's national health insurance; it was one of the campaign promises of [[President of France|President]] [[Emmanuel Macron]] and marked the first major social reform of his five-year term.<ref>Harriet Agnew (24 September 2019), [https://www.ft.com/content/6b5d2b5e-de11-11e9-b112-9624ec9edc59 France moves to extend IVF to gay and single women] ''[[Financial Times]]''.</ref><ref>[https://www.nouvelobs.com/societe/20190911.OBS18302/la-pma-post-mortem-rejetee-par-les-deputes.html La PMA post-mortem rejet\u00e9e par les d\u00e9put\u00e9s] ''[[L\u2019Obs]]'', 11 September 2019.</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, Berg\u00e9 caused controversy when she announced her intention to vote for a [[The Republicans (France)|Republican]] draft law written by [[\u00c9ric Ciotti]]\u00a0and banning the wearing of the [[hijab]] by women accompanying groups of students on school outings; as a response, five other LREM members \u2013 [[Coralie Dubost]], [[C\u00e9cile Rilhac]], [[Jean-Michel Mis]], [[St\u00e9phane Trompille]] and [[Eric Bothorel]] \u2013 disassociated themselves from her.<ref>Pierre Lepelletier (16 October 2019), [https://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/notinmyname-des-deputes-lrem-se-desolidarisent-d-aurore-berge-sur-le-voile-20191016 #NotInMyName: des d\u00e9put\u00e9s LREM se d\u00e9solidarisent d\u2019Aurore Berg\u00e9 sur le voile] ''[[Le Figaro]]''.</ref> \n\n==See also==\n* [[2017 French legislative election]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berge, Aurore}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sciences Po alumni]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 15th National Assembly of the French Fifth Republic]]\n[[Category:La R\u00e9publique En Marche politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century French women politicians]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Paris]]\n[[Category:Women members of the National Assembly (France)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{infobox officeholder\n| name        = Aurore Berg\u00e9\n| image       = Aurore Berg\u00e9.jpg\n| office      = Member of the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]]<br/>for [[Yvelines]]'s [[Yvelines's 10th constituency|10th]] constituency\n| term_start  = 21 June 2017\n| term_end    =\n| predecessor = [[Jean-Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Poisson]]\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1986|11|13|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Paris]], France\n| nationality = French\n| party       = [[Union for a Popular Movement]] {{small|(2002\u20132015)}}<br/>[[The Republicans (France)|The Republicans]] {{small|(2015\u20132017)}}<br/>[[La R\u00e9publique En Marche!]] {{small|(2017\u2013present)}}\n| alma_mater  = [[Sciences Po]]\n}}\n'''Aurore Berg\u00e9''' (born 13 November 1986) is a French politician who has been serving as a member of the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]] since 2017, representing [[Yvelines's 10th constituency]]. She is considered a close ally of [[President of France|President]] [[Emmanuel Macron]].<ref>C\u00e9dric Pietralunga and Alexandre Lemari\u00e9 (20 October 2017), [https://www.lemonde.fr/la-republique-en-marche/article/2017/10/20/enquete-sur-les-snipers-de-la-macronie_5203537_5126036.html La R\u00e9publique en marche: Les snipers de la Macronie] ''[[Le Monde]]''.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nA native of [[Paris]], Berg\u00e9 studied at [[Sciences Po]]. She became a member of the [[Union for a Popular Movement]] (UMP) in 2002;<ref>[https://www.lejdd.fr/Politique/les-10-deputes-qui-vont-peser-dans-le-quinquennat-3400187 Les 10 d\u00e9put\u00e9s qui vont peser dans le quinquennat] ''[[Le Journal du Dimanche]]'', 1 August 2017.</ref> when the party became [[The Republicans (France)|The Republicans]] (LR) in 2015, she joined it. In the [[2016 The Republicans (France) presidential primary|Republicans' primaries]] ahead of the [[2017 French presidential election|2017 presidential elections]], she campaigned for [[Alain Jupp\u00e9]].<ref>[https://www.lejdd.fr/Politique/les-10-deputes-qui-vont-peser-dans-le-quinquennat-3400187 Les 10 d\u00e9put\u00e9s qui vont peser dans le quinquennat] ''[[Le Journal du Dimanche]]'', 1 August 2017.</ref>\n\nBerg\u00e9 joined [[La R\u00e9publique En Marche!]] in 2017. She has also been a municipal councillor of [[Magny-les-Hameaux]] since the [[2014 French municipal elections|2014 elections]].<ref name=\"Bio\">{{Cite web|url=http://elections.interieur.gouv.fr/legislatives-2017/078/07810.html |title=Elections l\u00e9gislatives 2017 |accessdate=19 June 2017 |work=Ministry of the Interior |language=French}}</ref> In parliament, Berg\u00e9 serves as member of the Committee on Cultural Affairs and Education.<ref>[http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/deputes/fiche/OMC_PA722046 Aurore Berg\u00e9] [[National Assembly (France)|French National Assembly]].</ref>\n\nFrom 2017 until 2019, Berg\u00e9 served as one of her parliamentary group's spokespersons under the leadership of its successive chairmen [[Richard Ferrand]] and [[Gilles Le Gendre]].<ref>Mathilde Siraud (14 January 2019), [https://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/le-scan/coulisses/2019/01/14/25006-20190114ARTFIG00336-le-groupe-larem-a-l-assemblee-muscle-son-equipe-de-porte-paroles.php Le groupe LaREM \u00e0 l'Assembl\u00e9e muscle son \u00e9quipe de porte-parole] ''[[Le Figaro]]''.</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\nIn the [[2012 Union for a Popular Movement leadership election]], Berg\u00e9 supported [[Fran\u00e7ois Fillon]] as the party's leader.<ref>Nolwenn Le Blevennec (18 November 2016), [https://www.nouvelobs.com/rue89/rue89-politique/20131028.RUE9655/aurore-berge-26-ans-la-candidate-ump-qui-a-tout-pour-plaire-a-la-gauche.html Aurore Berg\u00e9, 26 ans, la candidate UMP qui a tout pour plaire \u00e0 la gauche] ''[[L'Obs|Le Nouvel Observateur]]''.</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, following the appointment of [[Fran\u00e7ois de Rugy]] to the government, Berg\u00e9 supported the candidacy of [[Richard Ferrand]] for the presidency of the National Assembly.<ref>Julie Cloris (9 September 2018), [http://www.leparisien.fr/politique/duel-ferrand-pompili-pour-presider-l-assemblee-qui-soutient-qui-09-09-2018-7881792.php Duel Ferrand-Pompili pour pr\u00e9sider l\u2019Assembl\u00e9e : qui soutient qui ?] ''[[Le Parisien]]''.</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Berg\u00e9 led (with [[Guillaume Chiche]]) a group of LREM members who advocated for of a bioethics law extending to homosexual and single women free access to [[Assisted reproductive technology|fertility treatments]] such as [[in vitro fertilisation]] (IVF) under France's national health insurance; it was one of the campaign promises of [[President of France|President]] [[Emmanuel Macron]] and marked the first major social reform of his five-year term.<ref>Harriet Agnew (September 24, 2019), [https://www.ft.com/content/6b5d2b5e-de11-11e9-b112-9624ec9edc59 France moves to extend IVF to gay and single women] ''[[Financial Times]]''.</ref><ref>[https://www.nouvelobs.com/societe/20190911.OBS18302/la-pma-post-mortem-rejetee-par-les-deputes.html La PMA post-mortem rejet\u00e9e par les d\u00e9put\u00e9s] ''[[L\u2019Obs]]'', 11 September 2019.</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, Berg\u00e9 caused controversy when she announced her intention to vote for a [[The Republicans (France)|Republican]] draft law written by [[\u00c9ric Ciotti]]\u00a0and banning the wearing of the [[hijab]] by women accompanying groups of students on school outings; as a response, five other LREM members \u2013 [[Coralie Dubost]], [[C\u00e9cile Rilhac]], [[Jean-Michel Mis]], [[St\u00e9phane Trompille]] and [[Eric Bothorel]] \u2013 disassociated themselves from her.<ref>Pierre Lepelletier (16 October 2019), [https://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/notinmyname-des-deputes-lrem-se-desolidarisent-d-aurore-berge-sur-le-voile-20191016 #NotInMyName: des d\u00e9put\u00e9s LREM se d\u00e9solidarisent d\u2019Aurore Berg\u00e9 sur le voile] ''[[Le Figaro]]''.</ref> \n\n==See also==\n* [[2017 French legislative election]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berge, Aurore}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sciences Po alumni]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 15th National Assembly of the French Fifth Republic]]\n[[Category:La R\u00e9publique En Marche politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century French women politicians]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Paris]]\n[[Category:Women members of the National Assembly (France)]]\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aurore_Berg%C3%A9"}
